    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "Dear Editor,",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Unlike other medical specialties, an adequate ophthalmological practice strongly relies on physical examination to reach the diagnosis, which involves close contact with the patient. Moreover, several ophthalmic tools such as the slit-lamp, the Goldmann tonometer, gonioscopy and fundus lenses, and the phoropter, among others are required to perform a complete eye evaluation. All of them come in close or direct contact with the patient and hence can favor nosocomial spread of infections. Droplet spread is the main route by which the novel coronavirus (SARS-CoV-2) is transmitted. Studies reveal droplet presence of SARS-CoV-2 on door handles, mobile phones, plastic, stainless steel, and other common contact surfaces [1]. The virus can stay on the surface for 2\u20133 days, increasing the risk of fomite infectivity [1]. To reduce the spread of SARS-CoV-2, certain steps must be included into the practice:ReschedulingElective procedures and patients with no ophthalmic emergency with confirmed or suspected coronavirus disease (COVID-19) should be judiciously rescheduled [2].In March 27, 2020, the American Academy of Ophthalmology enlisted the urgent and emergent procedures such as drainage of abscess, retinal detachment surgery, anterior segment, or cornea laceration repair, among others. The latter includes procedures aiming to resolve potential sight-threatening conditions [3].2)Before slit-lamp evaluation (SLE)Patients must wear a mask and perform hand washing with soap and water or 80% ethanol solution (80% ES) [4].A protective shield on the slit-lamp must be installed and cleaned up after each consultation to reduce droplet transmission.Ophthalmologists must wash hands and wear N95 masks, protective eyewear, and new gloves [5].Contact surfaces from the slit-lamp such as the applanation tonometer and chin and forehead support must be disinfected with 80% ES [4].3)During SLEAvoid talking and instruct the patient to do the same.Touching the patient\u2019s eye should be discouraged.Avoid Goldmann applanation tonometry. If strictly necessary, use disposable tips [2].If gonioscopy and fundus evaluation is required, disposable lens use and/or prior disinfection must be performed [5].4)After SLEClean the slit-lamp and all the surfaces exposed to the patient with an alcohol wipe.Both the patient and the ophthalmologist, prior glove removal, must wash their hands as mentioned above [2].5)Avoid unnecessary paperworkA digital patient record is preferred.",
